No — **WCAG 2.4.11 (Focus Visibility)** is about **visual focus indicators**, *not* focus trapping.

Confusing 2.4.11 with **2.1.2 (No Keyboard Trap)** or **1.3.2 (Meaningful Sequence)** is common. Here’s the correct breakdown:

| SC | Requirement | Applies to modals? |
|----|-------------|-------------------|
| **1.3.2** | Meaningful sequence | Ensure modal DOM order matches visual order |
| **2.1.2** | No Keyboard Trap | **Yes** — focus must be trapped *inside* the modal |
| **2.4.7** | Focus Visible (AA) | Modal’s active element must have visible focus |
| **2.4.11** | Focus Not Obscured (AA) | Focus indicator must **not be hidden behind other elements** |

✅ Correct implementation for modal focus management:
```ts
// 1. Trap focus (using aria-modal + role="dialog" + proper tabindex management)
// 2. Move focus to first focusable element on open
// 3. Restore focus to trigger element on close

const modal = document.getElementById('my-modal');
const firstFocusable = modal.querySelector('button, [href], input, select, textarea, [tabindex]:not([tabindex="-1"])');
firstFocusable?.focus();
```

✅ Validate focus visibility (2.4.11):
```ts
// Use @axe-core/playwright to check focus indicators aren’t clipped or hidden
await new AxeBuilder({ page })
  .withTags(['wcag22aa'])
  .include('#my-modal')
  .analyze();
// Checks: contrast, visibility, clipping, z-index overlap
```

2.4.11 ensures the focus ring is *visible*, not that focus is trapped.

